ions did not intentionally compete, there was a drift towards zero-sum outcomes which benefited national workforces in stronger structural positions. In the second process, during which a crisis resulting from the earlier actions of labour occurred, lack of solidarity reinforced effects of competition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / European.2bisacsh  aCompetition.  aCooperation.  aCrisis.  aDisintegration theory.  aDualization.  aEU.  aIntergovernmentalism.  aLabour movements.  aSocial-democratic parties.  aTrade unions.  aneofunctionalism.1 aProsser, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613665740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526136657423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526136657/original  a978-3-11-128277-0  Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles